Executive Summary

FirstEnergy Sammis Plant

RMP Plan



Background



FirstEnergy generates electricity at the Sammis power plant in Stratton, Ohio.  In order to reduce NOx air emissions, Sammis installed a Selective Catalytic Reduction (SCR) system on units 6&7 back in 2009.  This system removes NOx by catalytically reacting NOx with Ammonia to form Nitrogen and water vapor.  The process is covered by the EPA Risk Management Program (RMP) rules due to the presence of 29 % Aqueous Ammonia.



The covered process includes:  rail car unloading, tank truck unloading, storage, and SCR feed.  There are six storage tanks that may contain up to 57,000 gallons each (95% capacity).  There is also an emergency truck unloading and feed station.



Overview of the RMP Prevention Program 



The Sammis process is considered a Program 2 site by RMP rules.  However, FirstEnergy has chosen to implement additional elements of a Program 3 site.  Sammis uses a management of change and pre-startup safety review procedure as well conducting a compliance audit every three years following EPA guidelines.



Process protections are primarily those measures that will reduce, prevent or minimize a release from happening or, if it did happen, minimize the consequences of that threat.    These include:



Training on operations, emergencies etc;

   -Operators of the systems covered by the RMP plan have refresher training at least every 3 years.

Regular maintenance/SOPS;        

During deliveries, attendance by the operator is continuous until the delivery is complete;

No rail cars or tank trucks stored on site other than those in the process of being unloaded;

Onsite wireless communication;

Onsite trucks/vehicles for emergency transportation needs;   

Fire extinguishers; 

Ammonia monitors/detectors/alarms;

Main feed pump flow alarms/detector

High level tank alarms with interlock shutoffs  

